{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e6bf0a68-e423-4cc8-9a38-47ca1a2838ed","content":"Here's a step-by-step diagnostic and fix plan for your .NET MAUI build after a SDK upgrade on Windows 10.\n\n---\n\n## Phase 1 — Diagnose\n\nRun these commands in an **elevated** terminal (Admin PowerShell) to capture the current state:\n\n```powershell\n# 1. Which SDKs are installed?\ndotnet --list-sdks\n\n# 2. Which workloads does the NEW SDK see?\ndotnet workload list\n\n# 3. What does the build actually say?\ndotnet build YourApp.csproj -v diag 2>&1 | Select-String -Pattern \"error|workload|android\" | Select-Object -First 40\n```\n\nLook for these telltale errors:\n\n| Error pattern | Likely cause |\n|---|---|\n| `NETSDK1147` – workload not installed | Workloads from old SDK aren't registered for the new one |\n| `XA0000` / `XA5300` – Android SDK missing | Android SDK path not set or SDK packages outdated |\n| `MAUI` workload listed as **not installed** | Workload manifest mismatch after SDK update |\n\n---\n\n## Phase 2 — Fix workloads\n\n`dotnet workload update` **is safe** — it updates manifests and packs to match your current SDK band. It does not remove user data or project files.\n\n```powershell\n# 1. Clean stale manifests (safe, removes only workload install state)\ndotnet workload clean\n\n# 2. Update manifests + packs for the new SDK band\ndotnet workload update\n\n# 3. Re-install the MAUI workload explicitly (belt-and-suspenders)\ndotnet workload install maui\n\n# 4. Verify\ndotnet workload list          # should show: maui, android, ios, etc.\n```\n\n> **If you use Visual Studio** alongside the CLI, open **VS Installer → Modify** and confirm the **.NET MAUI** component is checked. VS manages its own workload copies; a mismatch between VS and CLI workloads is a common source of ghost errors.\n\n---\n\n## Phase 3 — Fix Android SDK\n\n```powershell\n# 1. Confirm the SDK path the build is using\ndotnet build -v diag 2>&1 | Select-String \"AndroidSdkDirectory\"\n\n# 2. If blank or wrong, set it explicitly in your .csproj or Directory.Build.props:\n#    <PropertyGroup>\n#      <AndroidSdkDirectory>C:\\Android\\android-sdk</AndroidSdkDirectory>\n#    </PropertyGroup>\n\n# 3. Accept pending licenses\n& \"$env:ANDROID_HOME\\cmdline-tools\\latest\\bin\\sdkmanager.bat\" --licenses\n\n# 4. Update Android platform packages to match the MAUI target\n& \"$env:ANDROID_HOME\\cmdline-tools\\latest\\bin\\sdkmanager.bat\" `\n    \"platforms;android-35\" \"build-tools;35.0.0\" \"platform-tools\"\n```\n\n---\n\n## Phase 4 — Verify\n\n```powershell\ndotnet clean\ndotnet build -t:Rebuild\n```\n\nA clean rebuild confirms both the workloads and the Android SDK are consistent with the new .NET SDK.\n\n---\n\n### Quick summary\n\n1. **Diagnose** — `dotnet --list-sdks`, `workload list`, and a diagnostic build.  \n2. **Workloads** — `workload clean` → `workload update` → `workload install maui`.  \n3. **Android SDK** — validate the path, accept licenses, install matching platform packages.  \n4. **Rebuild** — clean + rebuild to confirm.  \n\n`dotnet workload update` is non-destructive — your colleague's advice is sound; this plan just adds the diagnostic steps before and after so you can see exactly what changed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2dbfe9ef-d2e8-49f4-914e-287840ecbf2f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The directory is empty - no repository to explore. The user is asking for a diagnostic and fix plan. Let me provide a comprehensive plan based on my knowledge of .NET MAUI, workloads, and Android SDK issues on Windows 10.","outputTokens":990,"requestId":"482D:16F81E:7517437:8177213:69F3FBB6"},"id":"044bde2e-2c83-4318-8190-69a7aaeced14","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:03:07.411Z","parentId":"eb1fc02d-4054-4f6e-a34b-6d3a0ed8c886"}
